{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_017j59436GQQ1pSby4fNYzsN","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the KEY-QUESTIONS framework.\n\n**Behavior 1: Speech-to-text output preserves speaker labels so that the summary can attribute statements to specific attendees.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: Does the failure appear only when multiple modules interact? The behavior is about whether the speech-to-text API output includes speaker labels. This could fail at the STT API level (real API doesn't return labels) or at the parsing/transformation layer (labels get stripped). The key question is whether this is about the STT API's actual output format or about processing that output.\n- REAL-INFRA: The behavior says \"speech-to-text output preserves speaker labels\" — this implies the STT API is involved. \n\nThe real question is whether I'm testing the STT API's actual capability to return speaker labels, or whether I'm verifying that the processing pipeline doesn't strip them from a fixture response. If it's the former, that's a System-level test; if it's the latter, I need at least an Integration test that feeds a mock STT response through the full pipeline to confirm labels survive the transformation.\n\nBut speaker diarization itself is an AI/ML feature—it's non-deterministic and depends on the real model's behavior. I could mock the STT API with fixture data and verify the plumbing preserves labels, but that wouldn't catch the actual failure mode where the real STT model fails to correctly identify or label speakers. So this is really an Agentic test, with Integration as a fallback if I want to verify the pipeline doesn't accidentally strip labels.\n\nActually, I'm second-guessing the interpretation here. \"Preserves speaker labels\" could mean the downstream system keeps labels that the STT already produced, which would be Integration-testable by mocking labeled output. But the natural reading is that we're verifying the STT correctly identifies speakers in the first place and that those labels flow through to the summary—and that correctness depends on the AI model itself. I'll stick with Agentic as the minimum level.\n\nNow looking at the second behavior about action items for every attendee assigned a task.\n\nThis is fundamentally about whether the LLM correctly extracts and attributes action items from the transcript. The core failure mode isn't in the plumbing between modules—it's in the LLM's ability to identify which attendees got assigned what tasks. That's LLM-dependent and varies with model behavior, so this is Agentic. The question is whether we're testing just the summarization step in isolation (one Agentic step) or the full pipeline including STT (which would make it Workflow).\n\nFor the decisions behavior, I'm looking at whether key decisions get routed to the right section of the summary rather than buried in the narrative. Again, this is purely about LLM classification and extraction quality—the LLM has to identify decisions and place them correctly. I could mock the LLM output to test parsing, but that wouldn't actually verify the LLM puts decisions where they belong. The real failure mode requires real LLM behavior, so this is also Agentic.\n\nNow looking at the fourth behavior about handling long audio files—it seems the thought cuts off mid-sentence, but the pattern suggests this is about whether the service correctly segments files over 60 minutes and processes them sequentially before merging results.\n\nThe splitting logic itself could be Unit or Integration tested, and sequential processing through the pipeline could be Integration with mocked STT and LLM. But the coherence of the merged summary depends on the LLM's ability to synthesize results across segments, which requires real LLM behavior. The audio splitting itself doesn't need real infrastructure since libraries handle it in-process, though if the STT API has file size limits, testing with real files and real APIs might be necessary at the System level.\n\nThe full workflow involves multiple sequential agentic steps—splitting, then processing each segment through STT and LLM, then merging with a final LLM call for coherence. This multi-step orchestration makes it a Workflow-level test at minimum. Even if I mock the individual LLM outputs, the coherence verification specifically requires a real LLM merge step, so I can't fully test this behavior below Workflow.\n\nFor the complete pipeline—uploading real audio, transcribing with a real STT API, summarizing with LLM, and delivering structured output—that's clearly Workflow. It's end-to-end orchestration with real infrastructure and multiple agentic steps.\n\nNow I'm formalizing my assessment across all five behaviors. Speaker label preservation depends on real STT diarization capabilities, so that's Agentic-level testing. Action item extraction for task-assigned attendees requires LLM quality that mocks can't capture—also Agentic. Decision classification and routing through the LLM is similarly non-deterministic and needs real inference to validate.\n\nThe 60-minute splitting with coherent merging jumps to Workflow level because it chains multiple agentic steps together—per-segment STT and LLM processing followed by a merge LLM that needs to maintain consistency across the outputs. The full pipeline without manual intervention is explicitly Workflow, requiring real audio, real API calls, and multiple sequential agentic operations to work end-to-end.\n\nNow I'm checking whether each behavior's test description aligns with its assigned level. All five behaviors check out—the Agentic ones use real APIs or LLM calls as expected, and the Workflow ones involve multiple chained steps. For the test descriptions themselves, I need to write concrete scenarios that validate each behavior. Starting with the first one: I'd feed a real audio file with multiple speakers into the actual STT API and confirm that speaker labels persist through the entire pipeline and remain available when the summarization step runs.\n\nFor the remaining four, I'm laying out scenarios that test the LLM's ability to extract and structure task assignments by attendee, capture explicit decisions in the right output field, handle long audio files through segmented processing with real LLM calls at each stage, and finally validate the full end-to-end upload and processing flow through the service's actual endpoints.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9896,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9896},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c754463c-312d-4d9a-8479-82b4d8422eff","uuid":"c899349b-cfff-42fb-a176-9c24e9fd93b6"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_017j59436GQQ1pSby4fNYzsN","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01JAPCvNdmK4vRd16ukL2Rcj","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Speech-to-text output preserves speaker labels so the summary can attribute statements to specific attendees.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Speaker diarization (assigning labels like 'Speaker 1') is produced by the real STT AI/ML model. A mocked STT response with pre-injected labels only tests plumbing — it cannot reveal failures where the real model merges speakers, drops labels, or returns inconsistent speaker IDs across utterances. Correctness here depends on what the real STT model actually returns, making it non-deterministic across runs. REJECTION-GATE for Integration: an in-process mock STT fixture would always pass because it already has correct labels; the real failure mode (STT fails to diarize) is invisible at that level.","test_description":"Send a real short audio clip (≥2 identifiable speakers) through the actual STT API call; assert the returned transcript object contains per-utterance speaker identifiers (e.g., 'Speaker 1', 'Speaker 2') and that these labels survive serialization through the pipeline into the data structure passed to the summarization step.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.13,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.62,"Workflow":0.15}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The structured summary contains at least one action item for every attendee who was assigned a task during the meeting.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Extracting and correctly attributing action items to named attendees is LLM inference work. The failure mode — the LLM missing an assigned task or misattributing it — only surfaces with a real LLM call. A mocked LLM response would hard-code correct action items, hiding any extraction or attribution failure. The behavior's correctness criterion ('at least one action item for every task-assigned attendee') depends on real non-deterministic model output. REJECTION-GATE for Integration: a stub LLM returning a fixture response trivially passes; no real extraction quality is exercised. MULTI-STEP: only one summarization LLM call is needed given a fixed transcript, so Workflow is not required.","test_description":"Provide a realistic meeting transcript fixture containing explicit task assignments ('Alice will set up the staging environment', 'Bob will draft the proposal') to the real LLM summarizer; assert the returned structured output's action_items list contains at least one item attributed to Alice and at least one attributed to Bob.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.07,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.71,"Workflow":0.18}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Key decisions mentioned in the transcript appear in the 'decisions' section of the summary, not buried in the narrative.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Classifying a statement as a 'key decision' and routing it to the correct structured field (rather than a general narrative) is LLM inference behavior. The failure — the model leaving decisions in a narrative field — only appears with real model calls. A mock LLM trivially satisfies the assertion by returning pre-structured output. Running the real LLM 100 times on the same transcript could yield different routing decisions, confirming non-determinism. REJECTION-GATE for Integration: stub output always puts content in the right section; no routing failure is detectable. No additional agentic steps beyond the summarizer are needed, so Workflow is not required.","test_description":"Supply a transcript fixture containing clear decision statements (e.g., 'We have decided to migrate to the new database by Q3') to the real LLM summarizer; assert each such decision appears in the structured output's decisions field and is absent from any narrative/notes-only field.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.72,"Workflow":0.16}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When the audio file is longer than 60 minutes, the service splits it into segments and processes them sequentially, merging the results into a single coherent summary.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"This behavior chains multiple agentic steps: STT(segment 1) → LLM summarize(segment 1) → STT(segment 2) → LLM summarize(segment 2) → LLM merge into coherent summary. 'Coherent' means the merge step must produce output that correctly integrates context from both halves — a quality judgment that requires real LLM calls. The failure modes span both per-segment summarization quality and merge coherence, requiring at least two sequential real LLM calls. REJECTION-GATE for Agentic (single step): testing only the merge LLM call with fixture segment summaries misses failures where per-segment summarization drops context needed for coherent merging. The sequential multi-step dependency makes this Workflow.","test_description":"Construct or load a synthetic audio recording exceeding 60 minutes (or two stitched segments); run the full split-process-merge pipeline with real STT and real LLM calls for each segment and the merge step; assert the final output is a single structured summary document containing content derived from both the early and late portions of the recording with no contradictions or duplicate sections.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.07,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.23,"Workflow":0.62}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The full pipeline — upload audio, transcribe, summarize, deliver structured output — completes without manual intervention for a real meeting recording.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"This behavior is explicitly end-to-end: real HTTP audio upload, real STT API call, real LLM summarization call, and real delivery of structured output — all in sequence with no human step. Each agentic step (STT and LLM) is real and non-deterministic; multiple such steps are chained, satisfying both REAL-INFRA (real HTTP, real external APIs) and MULTI-STEP (≥2 sequential agentic steps). No lower level can simulate 'completes without manual intervention for a real meeting recording' because the behavior's correctness criterion is defined over the entire pipeline producing valid output. REJECTION-GATE for Agentic: testing only STT or only LLM misses failures at handoff boundaries (malformed transcript format passed to LLM, delivery endpoint rejecting output shape).","test_description":"Upload a real meeting recording file (5–15 minutes) through the service's upload endpoint; wait for the pipeline to complete asynchronously; assert that a structured output document is delivered (to a test delivery target) with non-empty action_items, decisions, and attendee_attributions fields, and that no human confirmation step was required at any stage.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.02,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.1,"Workflow":0.83}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9896,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9896},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c754463c-312d-4d9a-8479-82b4d8422eff","uuid":"118f1b47-0fe7-46d3-9612-6d243c4ce0d4"}
